AU  - Alston, Julian
AU  - Huang, Jikun
Y1  - 2005/08/01
PY  - 2005
DA  - 2005/08/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1468-2354.2005.00356.x
T2  - International Economic Review
JF  - International Economic Review
JO  - International Economic Review
SP  - 1033
EP  - 1057
VL  - 46
IS  - 3
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0020-6598
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1468-2354.2005.00356.x
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - This article investigates economies of scale and scope and other potential sources of improvements in the economic efficiency of China's crop breeding, an industry at the heart of the nation's food economy. Using data covering 46 wheat- and maize-breeding institutes from 1981 to 2000, we estimate cost functions for the production of new varieties at China's wheat- and maize-breeding institutes. Our results indicate strong economies of scale, along with small to moderate economies of scope related to the joint production of new wheat and maize varieties. Cost efficiency increases significantly with increases in the breeders' educational status and with increases in access to genetic materials from outside the institute.
ER  - 

